  "source": "Pediatrics_Nelson_textbook_data.txt - ABO incompatibility occurs in approximately 20-25% of pregnancies and is the most common cause of hemolytic disease of the newborn. The mother is usually blood group O, and the fetus is group A, B, or AB. The mother has naturally occurring anti-A and anti-B antibodies, which cross the placenta and cause hemolysis of fetal red blood cells. Unlike Rh incompatibility, ABO incompatibility can occur during the first pregnancy. The diagnosis is suggested by jaundice presenting within the first 24-48 hours of life, a positive direct Coombs test, and evidence of hemolysis (increased reticulocyte count, spherocytosis on peripheral blood smear). The hemolysis is usually mild to moderate, and severe hydrops fetalis is rare. Treatment options include phototherapy and, in severe cases, exchange transfusion.",
