  "source": "Surgery_Schwartz_textbook_data.txt - Acute cholangitis is a bacterial infection of the biliary tract, most commonly associated with biliary obstruction from gallstones. The classic presentation is Charcot's triad: right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, and fever with chills. The addition of altered mental status and hypotension (Reynolds' pentad) indicates a more severe form of the disease with high mortality. Management involves fluid resuscitation, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and biliary decompression. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) with sphincterotomy and stone extraction is the preferred method for biliary decompression. ERCP should be performed urgently (within 24-48 hours) in patients with severe cholangitis. For patients with mild to moderate cholangitis, ERCP can be performed semi-electively after initial stabilization with antibiotics. Percutaneous transhepatic biliary drainage (PTBD) is an alternative when ERCP is not feasible or unsuccessful. Surgery is reserved for patients who fail endoscopic and percutaneous approaches or those with complicated biliary tract disease.",
