  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Cholangiocarcinoma is a malignancy arising from the biliary epithelium of the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts. Risk factors include primary sclerosing cholangitis, choledochal cysts, and liver fluke infections (Clonorchis sinensis, Opisthorchis viverrini). Chronic liver fluke infection induces chronic inflammation and epithelial proliferation in the bile ducts, leading to malignant transformation. In endemic areas of Southeast Asia, where raw or undercooked fish consumption is common, liver fluke-associated cholangiocarcinoma is a major health problem. Patients typically present with painless jaundice, weight loss, and fatigue. Diagnosis relies on imaging studies (ultrasonography, CT, MRI/MRCP), tumor markers (CA 19-9, which may be elevated but is not specific), and sometimes endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) with brushings for cytology. Treatment options include surgical resection for localized disease, liver transplantation in selected cases, and palliative biliary drainage for unresectable tumors. Prognosis is generally poor, with 5-year survival rates of 5-10% for unresectable disease.",
