  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is a chronic, progressive cholestatic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of both intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts, leading to the formation of multiple bile duct strictures. PSC is strongly associated with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), particularly ulcerative colitis, which is present in approximately 70-80% of PSC patients. The disease typically affects young to middle-aged adults with a male predominance. Patients with PSC often present with fatigue, pruritus, and intermittent jaundice. Laboratory findings include elevated alkaline phosphatase and gamma-glutamyltransferase, and perinuclear antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (p-ANCA) are positive in 60-80% of patients. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) or endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) typically shows multifocal strictures and dilatations of the biliary tree, giving a characteristic 'beaded' appearance. PSC is associated with an increased risk of cholangiocarcinoma, colorectal cancer, and gallbladder cancer.",
