  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Ultrasound is the most widely used imaging technique for the diagnosis of cirrhosis and its complications. It is noninvasive, widely available, and relatively inexpensive. In patients with cirrhosis, ultrasound can reveal a nodular liver surface, liver size changes (often shrunken in advanced cirrhosis), splenomegaly, and signs of portal hypertension such as ascites and portosystemic collaterals. Doppler ultrasonography provides valuable information about blood flow direction and velocity in the portal vein and can detect portal vein thrombosis, a serious complication of cirrhosis. Additionally, ultrasound is an important screening tool for hepatocellular carcinoma in patients with cirrhosis. The hepatic venous pressure gradient (HVPG), a measure of the difference between wedged and free hepatic venous pressures, is the gold standard for assessing portal pressure. An HVPG >10 mmHg defines clinically significant portal hypertension and is predictive of complications such as variceal hemorrhage when >12 mmHg.",
