  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) is a chronic, progressive liver disease characterized by continuing hepatocellular inflammation and necrosis, with a tendency to progress to cirrhosis and liver failure. It predominantly affects women and is associated with circulating autoantibodies and elevated immunoglobulin G (IgG) levels. The disease can present with a wide spectrum of clinical manifestations, from asymptomatic elevation of liver enzymes to acute severe hepatitis or even fulminant hepatic failure. Extrahepatic autoimmune disorders, such as thyroiditis, rheumatoid arthritis, or ulcerative colitis, may coexist in 40% of patients. The diagnosis of AIH is based on a combination of clinical, biochemical, immunological, and histological features, and the exclusion of other causes of liver disease. The serological hallmarks include elevated serum IgG and the presence of autoantibodies, particularly antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and anti-smooth muscle antibodies (ASMA) in type 1 AIH, or anti-liver-kidney microsomal type 1 (anti-LKM1) antibodies in type 2 AIH. Liver biopsy typically shows interface hepatitis, lymphoplasmacytic infiltration, and hepatocyte rosetting. Corticosteroids, alone or in combination with azathioprine, remain the cornerstone of therapy.",
