  "source": "Surgery_Schwartz_textbook_data.txt - Perihilar cholangiocarcinoma (Klatskin tumor) is a malignancy arising from the biliary epithelium at or near the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts. The Bismuth-Corlette classification is used to describe the anatomic extent of these tumors: type I involves the common hepatic duct below the confluence; type II involves the confluence; type IIIA extends into the right hepatic duct; type IIIB extends into the left hepatic duct; and type IV involves both right and left hepatic ducts up to or beyond secondary biliary radicles. Surgical resection offers the only chance for cure, with 5-year survival rates of 20-40% for R0 resection. The surgical approach is determined by the tumor location and extent. Type IIIA tumors typically require right hepatectomy with caudate lobectomy to achieve negative margins, while type IIIB tumors require left hepatectomy with caudate lobectomy. Biliary drainage may be performed preoperatively in patients with severe hyperbilirubinemia or cholangitis, although its routine use remains controversial. Preoperative portal vein embolization may be necessary in patients with small future liver remnant. Liver transplantation may be considered in highly selected patients with early-stage unresectable hilar cholangiocarcinoma, particularly after neoadjuvant chemoradiation therapy.",
